Although lawmakers had previously cited a travel ban as a common-sense step to prevent more people with Ebola from entering the U.S., Obama defended his decision.

He argued that far from combating the spread of the deadly virus, such a ban would only hamper aid efforts and screening measures. 

Instead, he said defeating Ebola, which has mainly affected Liberia, Guinea and Sierra Leone, would require a joint effort between citizens, government leaders and the media.

On Friday, growing concern about Ebola and the three cases diagnosed so far in Dallas prompted Obama to tap former top White House adviser Ron Klain to be his point person on the virus.

